<Page
    x:Class="Salami.FunFactsPage"
    xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
    xmlns:local="using:Salami"
    xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
    xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
    mc:Ignorable="d">

    <ScrollViewer>
        <StackPanel Spacing="24" Padding="24">
            <!-- Header -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="12">
                <TextBlock Text="Amazing Salami Facts" 
                          FontSize="42" 
                          FontWeight="Bold"/>
                <TextBlock Text="Fascinating trivia about the world's favorite cured meat" 
                          FontSize="18" 
                          Opacity="0.8"/>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Hero Section -->
            <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                   CornerRadius="12" 
                   Padding="32">
                <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                    <TextBlock Text="Did You Know?" 
                              FontSize="36" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"
                              HorizontalAlignment="Center"/>
                    <TextBlock Text="Salami has a fascinating history spanning thousands of years and cultures. From space missions to world records, salami has been part of incredible stories!" 
                              FontSize="16"
                              Foreground="{StaticResource SalamiPink}"
                              TextAlignment="Center"
                              TextWrapping="Wrap"
                              HorizontalAlignment="Center"
                              MaxWidth="700"/>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <!-- Origins & Etymology -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiPink}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸ“š Origins &amp; Etymology" 
                              FontSize="28" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="{StaticResource SalamiRed}"/>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>The Word "Salami"</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            The word "salami" comes from the Italian verb "salare," which means "to salt." 
                            This refers to the salt-curing process that is essential to salami production. 
                            The ancient Romans called it "salumen" (salted meat), and the practice dates 
                            back to at least the Roman Empire.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Ancient Preservation</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            Before refrigeration, curing meat with salt was not just a culinary choiceâ€”it 
                            was a matter of survival. Ancient civilizations discovered that salt inhibits 
                            bacterial growth, allowing meat to be stored for months or even years. This 
                            made salami invaluable for long sea voyages, military campaigns, and surviving harsh winters.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Record-Breaking Salami -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸ† World Records" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"/>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Longest Salami Ever Made</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            In 2011, Hungarian salami makers created the world's longest salami at an 
                            incredible 1,120 meters (3,674 feet) long! This record-breaking salami required 
                            over 1,000 kilograms of meat and took weeks of preparation. It was displayed 
                            through the streets of a Hungarian town during a festival celebration.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Heaviest Salami</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            The heaviest single salami ever recorded weighed over 130 kilograms (286 pounds). 
                            It took several months to cure properly and required special equipment just to move it!
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Space & Exploration -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸš€ Salami in Space" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"/>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Astronaut Food</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            Salami has been taken on numerous space missions! Its shelf-stable nature, high 
                            protein content, and no need for refrigeration make it ideal for space travel. 
                            Russian cosmonauts particularly love salami and often request it for their missions. 
                            It provides a taste of home in the isolation of space.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Antarctic Expeditions</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            Early Antarctic explorers relied heavily on salami and other cured meats for 
                            sustenance during their expeditions. The famous expeditions of Shackleton and 
                            Scott included tons of cured meats in their provisions. Some of these salamis 
                            have been found perfectly preserved in Antarctic huts over 100 years later!
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Science & Production -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiPink}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸ”¬ Science of Salami" 
                              FontSize="28" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="{StaticResource SalamiRed}"/>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Beneficial Mold</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            The white coating you see on some salamis is intentional! It's a beneficial mold 
                            called Penicillium nalgiovense (a relative of the mold used to make penicillin). 
                            This mold protects the salami from harmful bacteria, regulates moisture loss, and 
                            contributes to flavor development. It's completely safe to eat!
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Natural Antibiotics</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            During fermentation, lactic acid bacteria produce compounds called bacteriocins, 
                            which are natural antibiotics. These compounds inhibit the growth of harmful 
                            microorganisms, making salami safe to eat without refrigeration. It's a fascinating 
                            example of using beneficial microbes to preserve food!
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>pH Changes</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            The pH of salami drops from around 6.0 to 4.8-5.2 during fermentation. This 
                            dramatic pH change is what makes salami shelf-stable and gives it that 
                            characteristic tangy flavor. The acidic environment prevents harmful bacteria 
                            from surviving.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Cultural Facts -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸŒ Cultural Trivia" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"/>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Protected Status</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            Several Italian salamis have PDO (Protected Designation of Origin) status, meaning 
                            they can only be made in specific regions using traditional methods. These include 
                            Salame Felino, Salame Piacentino, and Soppressata di Calabria. This legal protection 
                            preserves centuries of tradition and ensures authenticity.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Annual Production</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            Italy alone produces over 200,000 tons of salami annually! That's roughly equal to 
                            the weight of 40,000 elephants. The salami industry is worth billions of euros and 
                            employs tens of thousands of people across Europe.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Salami Festivals</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            There are dozens of salami festivals held annually across Europe. The Sagra del 
                            Salame in Felino, Italy attracts over 15,000 visitors who come to celebrate salami 
                            with tastings, demonstrations, and competitions. These festivals have been held for 
                            centuries in some towns!
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Surprising Facts -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiPink}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸ˜² Surprising Facts" 
                              FontSize="28" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="{StaticResource SalamiRed}"/>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="14">
                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Over 300 Varieties Worldwide</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                There are over 300 distinct varieties of salami produced around the world, each 
                                with unique spice blends, textures, and curing methods based on local traditions 
                                and available ingredients.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>

                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Temperature Sensitive</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Salami should ideally be stored between 50-60Â°F (10-15Â°C). Too cold and the fats 
                                solidify, muting flavors. Too warm and it can spoil or become overly dry. This is 
                                why traditional Italian homes often had cool cellars for curing.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>

                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Ancient Recipes Still Used</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Some Italian families have been using the same salami recipe for over 500 years! 
                                These recipes are closely guarded secrets passed down through generations. The 
                                exact blend of spices and the specific curing conditions are considered family treasures.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>

                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Salami Sommelier</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Yes, salami sommeliers exist! In Italy, expert tasters can identify a salami's 
                                region of origin, age, and ingredients just by taste and smell. It takes years 
                                of training to develop this level of expertise.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>

                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Aging Rooms</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Traditional salami aging rooms are works of art. They're carefully designed with 
                                specific ventilation patterns, humidity controls, and temperature regulation. Some 
                                rooms have been in continuous use for over 200 years!
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>

                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Weight Loss During Aging</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                A salami loses 30-40% of its weight during the aging process as moisture 
                                evaporates. This concentration is what creates the intense flavors we love. 
                                A salami that started at 1 kg might end up at just 600-700 grams!
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Economic Impact -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸ’° Economic Impact" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"/>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Multi-Billion Euro Industry</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            The European salami industry is worth billions of euros annually. In Italy alone, 
                            it's a major part of the agricultural economy, supporting pig farmers, spice 
                            producers, packaging companies, and thousands of small artisan producers.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                            <Bold>Tourism Impact</Bold>
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            Salami tourism is real! Thousands of visitors travel to Italian regions specifically 
                            to visit salami producers, attend festivals, and learn about traditional production 
                            methods. Some producers offer tours and tastings that attract food enthusiasts from 
                            around the world.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Health & Nutrition -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiPink}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸ¥— Nutrition Facts" 
                              FontSize="28" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="{StaticResource SalamiRed}"/>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="14">
                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>High in Protein</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Salami is an excellent source of protein, with about 20-25 grams per 100 grams. 
                                This made it invaluable for travelers, soldiers, and workers who needed 
                                concentrated nutrition.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>

                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Rich in B Vitamins</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Salami contains significant amounts of B vitamins, particularly B12, which is 
                                essential for energy metabolism and red blood cell formation. The fermentation 
                                process actually increases some vitamin content!
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>

                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Mineral Content</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Salami provides iron, zinc, and selenium. Iron is crucial for oxygen transport 
                                in the blood, zinc supports immune function, and selenium acts as an antioxidant.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Fun Modern Facts -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸŽ‰ Modern Salami Culture" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"/>
                </Border>

                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="14">
                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Social Media Star</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Charcuterie boards featuring salami have become incredibly popular on social 
                                media, with millions of posts on Instagram. Some influencers specialize entirely 
                                in creating artistic salami presentations!
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>

                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Craft Salami Movement</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                There's been a renaissance of artisanal salami production worldwide. Small-batch 
                                producers in North America, Australia, and even Asia are creating unique varieties 
                                using traditional techniques with local ingredients.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>

                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="18">
                                <Bold>Salami in Pop Culture</Bold>
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Salami has appeared in countless movies, TV shows, and literature as a symbol of 
                                Italian heritage and quality food. It's become an icon of Mediterranean cuisine 
                                recognized worldwide.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Final Amazing Fact -->
            <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                   CornerRadius="12" 
                   Padding="40">
                <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                    <TextBlock Text="ðŸŒŸ The Ultimate Salami Fact" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"
                              HorizontalAlignment="Center"/>
                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" 
                              FontSize="20"
                              Foreground="{StaticResource SalamiPink}"
                              TextAlignment="Center"
                              HorizontalAlignment="Center"
                              MaxWidth="700">
                        Despite being made for thousands of years, salami production remains largely 
                        artisanal. No two salamis are exactly alike - each one is unique, influenced by 
                        the maker's hand, local climate, and countless subtle variables. That's the 
                        magic of salami!
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Page>
